<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2></=
div>
<p>The English word <i>war</i> derives from the 11th-century <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_English" title=3D"Old English">Old English</=
a> words <span title=3D"Old English (ca. 450-1100)-language text"><i lang=
=3D"ang">wyrre</i></span> and <span title=3D"Old English (ca. 450-1100)-lan=
guage text"><i lang=3D"ang">werre</i></span>, from <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Old_French" title=3D"Old French">Old French</a> <span titl=
e=3D"Old French (842-ca. 1400)-language text"><i lang=3D"fro">werre</i></sp=
an> (<span title=3D"French-language text"><i lang=3D"fr">guerre</i></span> =
as in modern French), in turn from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Frankish_language" title=3D"Frankish language">Frankish</a> <span titl=
e=3D"Old Frankish-language text">*<i lang=3D"frk">werra</i></span>, ultimat=
ely deriving from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proto-German=
ic_language" title=3D"Proto-Germanic language">Proto-Germanic</a> <span tit=
le=3D"Proto-Germanic-language text">*<i lang=3D"gem">werz=C5=8D</i></span> =
<span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span class=3D"gloss-text">mixture, conf=
usion</span><span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span>. The word is related to the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Saxon" title=3D"Old Saxon">Ol=
d Saxon</a> <span title=3D"Old Saxon-language text"><i lang=3D"osx">werran<=
/i></span>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_High_German" title=
=3D"Old High German">Old High German</a> <span title=3D"Old High German (ca=
. 750-1050)-language text"><i lang=3D"goh">werran</i></span>, and the moder=
n German <span title=3D"German-language text"><i lang=3D"de">verwirren</i><=
/span>, meaning <span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span class=3D"gloss-tex=
t">to confuse, to perplex, to bring into confusion</span><span class=3D"glo=
ss-quot">'</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_history" ti=
tle=3D"Military history">Military history</a></div><p>Anthropologists disag=
ree about whether warfare was common throughout human prehistory, or whethe=
r it was a more recent development, following the invention of agriculture =
or organised states.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-:3-6"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wa=
r#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#c=
ite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is diffic=
ult to determine whether warfare occurred during the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Paleolithic" title=3D"Paleolithic">Paleolithic</a> due t=
o the sparseness of known remains. Some sources claim that most Middle and =
Upper Paleolithic societies were possibly fundamentally <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egalitarianism" title=3D"Egalitarianism">egalitarian<=
/a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-12"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-14"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> and may have rarely or never engaged in organized violence betwe=
en groups (i.e. war).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#c=
ite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Barbara_Ehrenreich_17-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Barba=
ra_Ehrenreich-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kelly_18-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Kelly-18"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> Evidence of violent conflict appears to increase during the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesolithic" title=3D"Mesolithic">Mesolith=
ic</a> period, from around 10,000 years ago onwards.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3_=
6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_=
note-:3-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>American cultural anthropologist and ethnologist <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raymond_Case_Kelly" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ra=
ymond Case Kelly">Raymond Case Kelly</a> claimed that before 400,000 years =
ago humans clashed like groups of chimpanzees; however, later they preferre=
d "positive and peaceful social relations between neighboring groups, such =
as joint hunting, trading, and courtship".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-19"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> In his book <i>Warless Societies and the Origin of War</i> he explor=
es the origins of modern wars and states that high surplus product encourag=
es conflict, so "raiding often begins in the richest environments".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/War#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =20
</p><p>In his 1996 book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_Bef=
ore_Civilization" title=3D"War Before Civilization">War Before Civilization=
</a></i>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lawrence_H._Keeley" titl=
e=3D"Lawrence H. Keeley">Lawrence H. Keeley</a>, a professor at the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Illinois_at_Urbana%E2%80%93=
Champaign" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"University of Illinois at Urbana=
=E2=80=93Champaign">University of Illinois</a>, says approximately 90=E2=80=
=9395% of known societies throughout history engaged in at least occasional=
 warfare,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
0<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and many fought constantly=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/War#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Keeley describes several styles of=
 primitive combat such as small <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ra=
id_(military)" title=3D"Raid (military)">raids</a>, large raids, and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massacre" title=3D"Massacre">massacres</=
a>. All of these forms of warfare were used by primitive societies, a findi=
ng supported by other researchers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-23"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Keeley explains that early war raids were not well organized, as the parti=
cipants did not have any formal training. Scarcity of resources meant <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defensive_works" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Defensive works">defensive works</a> were not a cost-effective way=
 to protect the society against enemy raids.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Keeley_page=
_55_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#=
cite_note-Keeley_page_55-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/William_Rubinstein" title=3D"William Rubinstein">William Rubinstein<=
/a> wrote "Pre-literate societies, even those organized in a relatively adv=
anced way, were renowned for their studied cruelty.'"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_not=
e-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Since the rise of the state some 5,000 years ago,<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_=
note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> military activity has continued over much of the globe=
. In Europe the oldest known battlefield is thought to date to 1250 BC.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/War#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Bronze_Age" title=3D"Bronze Age">Bronze Age</a> has been described a=
s a key period in the intensification of warfare, with the emergence of ded=
icated warriors and the development of metal weapons like swords.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
War#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Two other commonly named periods of increase =
are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axial_Age" title=3D"Axial =
Age">Axial Age</a> and Modern Times.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-29"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 The invention of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunpowder" title=
=3D"Gunpowder">gunpowder</a>, and its eventual use in warfare, together wit=
h the acceleration of technological advances, have fomented major changes t=
o war itself.
</p>
