=3D"2790" data-file-height=3D"1860"></a><figcaption>American tanks moving i=
n formation during the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gulf_War" t=
itle=3D"Gulf War">Gulf War</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Since 1945, great power wars, interstate wars,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-36=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conquest" title=3D"C=
onquest">territorial conquests</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Declaration_of_war" title=3D"Declaration of war">war declarations</a> =
have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Peace" title=3D"Long Pea=
ce">declined in frequency</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_37-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-:4-37"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Wars have been increasingly regulated by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/International_humanitarian_law" title=3D"International humanitari=
an law">international humanitarian law</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_37-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-:4-=
37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Battle deaths and casualties have declined, in part due to =
advances in military medicine<sup id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and de=
spite advances in weapons. In Western Europe, since the late 18th century, =
more than 150 conflicts and about 600 battles have taken place, but no batt=
le has taken place since 1945.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-War_39-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-War-39"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>However, war in some aspects has not necessarily declined.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-:4_37-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/War#cite_note-:4-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Civil_war" title=3D"Civil war">Civil wars</a> have increased in absolut=
e terms since 1945.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_37-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-:4-37"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A distin=
ctive feature of war since 1945 is that combat has largely been a matter of=
 civil wars and insurgencies.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The ma=
jor exceptions were the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korean_War=
" title=3D"Korean War">Korean War</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Indo-Pakistani_War_of_1971" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Indo-Pa=
kistani War of 1971">Indo-Pakistani War of 1971</a>, the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iran%E2%80%93Iraq_War" title=3D"Iran=E2=80=93Iraq Wa=
r">Iran=E2=80=93Iraq War</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Gulf_War" title=3D"Gulf War">Gulf War</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Eritrean%E2%80%93Ethiopian_War" title=3D"Eritrean=E2=80=93Ethi=
opian War">Eritrean=E2=80=93Ethiopian War</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russo-Ukrainian_War" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ru=
sso-Ukrainian War">Russo-Ukrainian War</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Types_of_warfare">Types of =
warfare</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outline_of_war#Types=
_of_war" title=3D"Outline of war">Types of war</a></div>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asymmetric_warfare" title=
=3D"Asymmetric warfare">Asymmetric warfare</a> is the methods used in confl=
icts between <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belligerent" title=3D=
"Belligerent">belligerents</a> of drastically different levels of military =
capability or size.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biological_warfare" title=3D"B=
iological warfare">Biological warfare</a>, or germ warfare, is the use of b=
iological infectious agents or toxins such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Bacteria" title=3D"Bacteria">bacteria</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virus" title=3D"Virus">viruses</a>, and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fungus" title=3D"Fungus">fungi</a> against peopl=
e, plants, or animals. This can be conducted through sophisticated technolo=
gies, like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_munition" title=
=3D"Cluster munition">cluster munitions</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-42"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> or with rudimentary techniques like catapulting an infected corp=
se behind enemy lines,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and can inc=
lude weaponized or non-weaponized pathogens.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_warfare" title=3D"Che=
mical warfare">Chemical warfare</a> involves the use of weaponized chemical=
s in combat. Poison gas as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemi=
cal_warfare" title=3D"Chemical warfare">chemical weapon</a> was principally=
 used during <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_I" title=3D=
"World War I">World War I</a>, and resulted in over a million estimated cas=
ualties, including more than 100,000 civilians.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-44">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cold_warfare" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Cold warfare">Cold warfare</a> is an intense international r=
ivalry without direct military conflict, but with a sustained threat of it,=
 including high levels of military preparations, expenditures, and developm=
ent, and may involve active conflicts by indirect means, such as <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_warfare" title=3D"Economic warfare"=
>economic warfare</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_w=
arfare" title=3D"Political warfare">political warfare</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covert_operation" title=3D"Covert operation">cover=
t operations</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Espionage" title=
=3D"Espionage">espionage</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cybe=
rwarfare" title=3D"Cyberwarfare">cyberwarfare</a>, or <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proxy_war" title=3D"Proxy war">proxy wars</a>.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conventional_warfare" title=3D=
"Conventional warfare">Conventional warfare</a> is a form of warfare betwee=
n states in which <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_weapon" =
title=3D"Nuclear weapon">nuclear</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Biological_weapon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Biological weapon">bi=
ological</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_weapons" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chemical weapons">chemical</a> or <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiological_warfare" title=3D"Radiological wa=
rfare">radiological weapons</a> are not used or see limited deployment.</li=
>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyberwarfare" title=3D"Cyberwa=
rfare">Cyberwarfare</a> involves the actions by a nation-state or internati=
onal organization to attack and attempt to damage another nation's informat=
ion systems.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insurgency" title=3D"Insurgenc=
y">Insurgency</a> is a rebellion against authority, where irregular forces =
take up arms to change an existing political order. An insurgency can be fo=
ught via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counterinsurgency" title=
=3D"Counterinsurgency">counterinsurgency</a>, and may also be opposed by me=
asures to protect the population, and by political and economic actions of =
various kinds aimed at undermining the insurgents' claims against the incum=
bent regime.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_warfare" title=3D"=
Information warfare">Information warfare</a> is the application of destruct=
ive force on a large scale against information assets and systems, against =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer" title=3D"Computer">c=
omputers</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_network"=
 title=3D"Computer network">networks</a> that support the four critical inf=
rastructures (the power grid, communications, financial, and transportation=
).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-45" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>44<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_warfare" title=3D"Nucl=
ear warfare">Nuclear warfare</a> is warfare in which <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_weapon" title=3D"Nuclear weapon">nuclear weapons=
</a> are the primary, or a major, method of achieving capitulation.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiological_warfare" title=3D=
"Radiological warfare">Radiological warfare</a> is any form of warfare invo=
lving deliberate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radioactive_conta=
mination" title=3D"Radioactive contamination">radiation poisoning or contam=
ination</a> of an area with radiological sources.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_war" title=3D"Total war"=
>Total war</a> is warfare by any means possible, disregarding the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laws_of_war" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Laws of war">laws of war</a>, placing no limits on <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legitimate_military_target" title=3D"Legitimate milita=
ry target">legitimate military targets</a>, using <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Weapon" title=3D"Weapon">weapons</a> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_tactics" title=3D"Military tactics">tactics=
</a> resulting in significant <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civi=
lian_casualties" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Civilian casualties">civili=
an casualties</a>, or demanding a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
War_effort" title=3D"War effort">war effort</a> requiring significant sacri=
fices by the friendly civilian population.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unconventional_warfare" title=
=3D"Unconventional warfare">Unconventional warfare</a> can be defined as "m=
ilitary and quasi-military operations other than <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Conventional_warfare" title=3D"Conventional warfare">convent=
ional warfare</a>"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nagao_definition_46-0" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-nagao_definiti=
on-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> and may use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cov=
ert_operation" title=3D"Covert operation">covert</a> forces or actions such=
 as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subversion" title=3D"Subversio=
n">subversion</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decoy" title=3D=
"Decoy">diversion</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sabotage" t=
itle=3D"Sabotage">sabotage</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Es=
pionage" title=3D"Espionage">espionage</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Biowarfare" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Biowarfare">biowarfare=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_sanctions" title=3D=
"Economic sanctions">sanctions</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Propaganda" title=3D"Propaganda">propaganda</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Guerrilla_warfare" title=3D"Guerrilla warfare">guerrilla=
 warfare</a>.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Aims">Aims</h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Flickr_-_DVIDSHUB_-_Firefight_in_the_Waterpur=
_Valley.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikim=
edia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Flickr_-_DVIDSHUB_-_Firefight_in_the_=
Waterpur_Valley.jpg/250px-Flickr_-_DVIDSHUB_-_Firefight_in_the_Waterpur_Val=
ley.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"168" class=3D"mw-file-e=
lement" data-file-width=3D"2100" data-file-height=3D"1410"></a><figcaption>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Army" title=3D"Unite=
d States Army">United States Army</a> soldiers engaged in a firefight with =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taliban_insurgency" title=3D"Talib=
an insurgency">Taliban insurgents</a> during the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%932021)" title=3D"War in Afgh=
anistan (2001=E2=80=932021)">War in Afghanistan</a>, 2009</figcaption></fig=
ure>
<p>Entities contemplating going to war and entities considering whether to =
end a war may formulate <i>war aims</i> as an evaluation/propaganda tool. W=
ar aims may stand as a proxy for national-military resolve.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#ci=
te_note-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h3>=
</div>
<p>Fried defines war aims as "the desired territorial, economic, military o=
r other benefits expected following successful conclusion of a war".<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/War#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Classification">Classificat=
ion</h3></div>
<p>Tangible/intangible aims:
</p>
<ul><li>Tangible war aims may involve (for example) the acquisition of terr=
itory (as in the German goal of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le=
bensraum" title=3D"Lebensraum">Lebensraum</a> in the first half of the 20th=
 century) or the recognition of economic concessions (as in the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-Dutch_Wars" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Anglo-Dutch Wars">Anglo-Dutch Wars</a>).</li>
<li>Intangible war aims =E2=80=93 like the accumulation of credibility or r=
eputation<sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =E2=80=93 may have more ta=
ngible expression ("conquest restores prestige, annexation increases power"=
).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Explicit/implicit aims:
</p>
<ul><li>Explicit war aims may involve published policy decisions.</li>
<li>Implicit war aims<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> can take the f=
orm of minutes of discussion, memoranda and instructions.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite=
_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Positive/negative aims:
</p>
<ul><li>"Positive war aims" cover tangible outcomes.</li>
<li>"Negative war aims" forestall or prevent undesired outcomes.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
ar#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>War aims can change in the course of conflict and may eventually morph i=
nto "peace conditions"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =E2=80=93 t=
he minimal conditions under which a state may cease to wage a particular wa=
r.
</p>
