<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"On_military_personnel">On m=
ilitary personnel</h3></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_personnel" title=3D"Mi=
litary personnel">Military personnel</a> subject to combat in war often suf=
fer mental and physical injuries, including depression, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posttraumatic_stress_disorder" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Posttraumatic stress disorder">posttraumatic stress disorder</a>, =
disease, injury, and death.
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>In every war in which American soldi=
ers have fought in, the chances of becoming a psychiatric casualty =E2=80=
=93 of being debilitated for some period of time as a consequence of the st=
resses of military life =E2=80=93 were greater than the chances of being ki=
lled by enemy fire.</p></blockquote><div class=3D"templatequotecite"><p sty=
le=3D"display: inline; padding-left: 2.3em;">=E2=80=94=E2=80=8A<i>No More H=
eroes</i>, Richard Gabriel<sup id=3D"cite_ref-War_39-1" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-War-39"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<span style=3D"display:none" data-plural=3D"0"></span></p></div>
<p>Swank and Marchand's World War II study found that after sixty days of c=
ontinuous combat, 98% of all surviving military personnel will become psych=
iatric casualties. Psychiatric casualties manifest themselves in fatigue ca=
ses, confusional states, conversion hysteria, anxiety, obsessional and comp=
ulsive states, and character disorders.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-autogenerated199=
6_96-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#ci=
te_note-autogenerated1996-96"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>One-tenth of mobilised A=
merican men were hospitalised for mental disturbances between 1942 and 1945=
, and after thirty-five days of uninterrupted combat, 98% of them manifeste=
d psychiatric disturbances in varying degrees.</p></blockquote><div class=
=3D"templatequotecite"><p style=3D"display: inline; padding-left: 2.3em;">=
=E2=80=94=E2=80=8A<i>14=E2=80=9318: Understanding the Great War</i>, St=C3=
=A9phane Audoin-Rouzeau, Annette Becker<sup id=3D"cite_ref-War_39-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-War-3=
9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><span style=3D"display:none" data-plural=3D"0"></span></p></d=
iv>
<p>Additionally, it has been estimated anywhere from 18% to 54% of Vietnam =
war veterans suffered from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posttra=
umatic_stress_disorder" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Posttraumatic stress=
 disorder">posttraumatic stress disorder</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-autogenera=
ted1996_96-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
War#cite_note-autogenerated1996-96"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Based on 1860 census figures, 8% of all white American males aged 13=
 to 43 died in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Civil_=
War" title=3D"American Civil War">American Civil War</a>, including about 6=
% in the North and approximately 18% in the South.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-97" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-9=
7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>96<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> The war remains the deadliest conflict in American history, =
resulting in the deaths of 620,000 military personnel. <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_military_casualties_of_war" title=3D"Uni=
ted States military casualties of war">United States military casualties of=
 war</a> since 1775 have totaled over two million. Of the 60&nbsp;million E=
uropean military personnel who were mobilized in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/World_War_I" title=3D"World War I">World War I</a>, 8&nbsp;m=
illion were killed, 7&nbsp;million were permanently disabled, and 15&nbsp;m=
illion were seriously injured.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-98" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-98"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>97<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:DeadCrowIndians1874.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/0/0a/DeadCrowIndians1874.jpg/250px-DeadCrowIndians1874.jpg" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"157" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"640" data-file-height=3D"403"></a><figcaption>The remains=
 of dead <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crow_Indians" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Crow Indians">Crow Indians</a> killed and scalped by Si=
oux <abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=
=80=891874</span></figcaption></figure>
<p>During <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Napoleon_I_of_France" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Napoleon I of France">Napoleon</a>'s retreat f=
rom Moscow, more French military personnel died of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Typhus" title=3D"Typhus">typhus</a> than were killed by th=
e Russians.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-99" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-99"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>98<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Of the 450,000 soldiers =
who crossed the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neman_River" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Neman River">Neman</a> on 25 June 1812, less than=
 40,000 returned. More military personnel were killed from 1500 to 1914 by =
typhus than from military action.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-TIME_Magazine_1940_100=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_n=
ote-TIME_Magazine_1940-100"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>99<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In addition, if it were not for mod=
ern medical advances there would be thousands more dead from disease and in=
fection. For instance, during the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Seven_Years%27_War" title=3D"Seven Years' War">Seven Years' War</a>, the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Navy" title=3D"Royal Navy">Roy=
al Navy</a> reported it conscripted 184,899 sailors, of whom 133,708 (72%) =
died of disease or were 'missing'.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-101" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-101"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>100<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> It is estimated that between 1985 and 1994, 378,000 people per year died =
due to war.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-102" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-102"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>101<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"On_civilians">On civilians<=
/h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civilian_casualties" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Civilian casualties">Civilian casualties</a></d=
iv>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hanging_from_The_Miseries_and=
_Misfortunes_of_War_by_Jacques_Callot.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><i=
mg src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Hanging=
_from_The_Miseries_and_Misfortunes_of_War_by_Jacques_Callot.jpg/330px-Hangi=
ng_from_The_Miseries_and_Misfortunes_of_War_by_Jacques_Callot.jpg" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"131" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"5446" data-file-height=3D"2379"></a><figcaption><i><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Les_Grandes_Mis%C3%A8res_de_la_guerre" title=3D"=
Les Grandes Mis=C3=A8res de la guerre">Les Grandes Mis=C3=A8res de la guerr=
e</a></i> depict the destruction unleashed on civilians during the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thirty_Years%27_War" title=3D"Thirty Year=
s' War">Thirty Years' War</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Most wars have resulted in significant loss of life, along with destruct=
ion of infrastructure and resources (which may lead to <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Famine" title=3D"Famine">famine</a>, disease, and deat=
h in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civilian" title=3D"Civili=
an">civilian</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Population" title=
=3D"Population">population</a>). During the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Thirty_Years%27_War" title=3D"Thirty Years' War">Thirty Years' Wa=
r</a> in Europe, the population of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Holy_Roman_Empire" title=3D"Holy Roman Empire">Holy Roman Empire</a> w=
as reduced by 15 to 40 percent.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-103" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-103"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>102<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-104" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/War#cite_note-104"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>103<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Civilians in war zones may also be=
 subject to war atrocities such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Genocide" title=3D"Genocide">genocide</a>, while survivors may suffer the =
psychological aftereffects of witnessing the destruction of war. War also r=
esults in lower quality of life and worse health outcomes. A medium-sized c=
onflict with about 2,500 battle deaths reduces civilian life expectancy by =
one year and increases <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infant_mort=
ality" title=3D"Infant mortality">infant mortality</a> by 10% and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malnutrition" title=3D"Malnutrition">maln=
utrition</a> by 3.3%. Additionally, about 1.8% of the population loses acce=
ss to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drinking_water" title=3D"Dri=
nking water">drinking water</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-105" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-105"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>104<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p><p>Most estimates of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War=
_II_casualties" title=3D"World War II casualties">World War II casualties</=
a> indicate around 60&nbsp;million people died, 40&nbsp;million of whom wer=
e civilians.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-106" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-106"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>105<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Deaths in the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soviet_Union" title=3D"Soviet Union">Sov=
iet Union</a> were around <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Wa=
r_II_casualties_of_the_Soviet_Union" title=3D"World War II casualties of th=
e Soviet Union">27<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>million</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-107" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/War#cite_note-107"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>106<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Since a high proportion of those kille=
d were young men who had not yet fathered any children, population growth i=
n the postwar Soviet Union was much lower than it otherwise would have been=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-108" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-108"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>107<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Economic">Economic</h3></di=
v>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_Keynesianism" t=
itle=3D"Military Keynesianism">Military Keynesianism</a></div>
<p>Once a war has ended, losing nations are sometimes required to pay <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_reparations" title=3D"War reparatio=
ns">war reparations</a> to the victorious nations. In certain cases, land i=
s ceded to the victorious nations. For example, the territory of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alsace-Lorraine" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Alsace-Lorraine">Alsace-Lorraine</a> has been traded between France and=
 Germany on three different occasions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-109" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-109"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>108<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p><p>Typically, war becomes intertwined with the economy and many wars ar=
e partially or entirely based on economic reasons. The common view among ec=
onomic historians is that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grea=
t_Depression" title=3D"Great Depression">Great Depression</a> ended with th=
e advent of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II" title=3D=
"World War II">World War II</a>. Many economists believe that government sp=
ending on the war caused or at least accelerated recovery from the Great De=
pression, though some consider that it did not play a very large role in th=
e recovery, though it did help in reducing unemployment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Britannica1_110-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/War#cite_note-Britannica1-110"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
09<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Galbra=
ith_111-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War=
#cite_note-Galbraith-111"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>110<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-112" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-112"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>111<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-113" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-113"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>112=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In most cases, such as the =
wars of Louis XIV, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franco-Prus=
sian_War" title=3D"Franco-Prussian War">Franco-Prussian War</a>, and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_I" title=3D"World War I">World=
 War I</a>, warfare primarily results in damage to the economy of the count=
ries involved. For example, Russia's involvement in World War I took such a=
 toll on the Russian economy that it almost collapsed and greatly contribut=
ed to the start of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russian_Rev=
olution_of_1917" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Russian Revolution of 1917"=
>Russian Revolution of 1917</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-114" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-114"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>113<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"World_War_II">World War II<=
/h4></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Cyprian_War.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description=
"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a7/Cyp=
rian_War.jpg/250px-Cyprian_War.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"190" height=
=3D"248" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"589" data-file-height=
=3D"768"></a><figcaption>Ruins of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Warsaw" title=3D"Warsaw">Warsaw</a>'s Napoleon Square in the aftermath of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II" title=3D"World War II=
">World War II</a></figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II" title=3D"World Wa=
r II">World War II</a> was the most financially costly conflict in history;=
 its belligerents cumulatively spent about a trillion U.S. dollars on the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_effort" title=3D"War effort">wa=
r effort</a> (as adjusted to 1940 prices).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-115" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-115"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>114<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-116" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-116"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>115<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Depression" title=3D"Gre=
at Depression">Great Depression</a> of the 1930s ended as nations increased=
 their production of war materials.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-117" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-117"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>116<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p>By the end of the war, 70% of European industrial infrastructure was=
 destroyed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-118" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-118"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>117<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Property damage in th=
e Soviet Union inflicted by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ea=
stern_Front_(World_War_II)" title=3D"Eastern Front (World War II)">Axis inv=
asion</a> was estimated at a value of 679&nbsp;billion rubles. The combined=
 damage consisted of complete or partial destruction of 1,710 cities and to=
wns, 70,000 villages/hamlets, 2,508 church buildings, 31,850 industrial est=
ablishments, 40,000&nbsp;mi (64,374&nbsp;km) of railroad, 4100 railroad sta=
tions, 40,000 hospitals, 84,000 schools, and 43,000 public libraries.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-119" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/War#cite_note-119"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>118<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Theories_of_motivation">The=
ories of motivation</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_relations_=
theory" title=3D"International relations theory">International relations th=
eory</a></div>
<p>There are many theories about the motivations for war, but no consensus =
about which are most common.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-120" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-120"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>119<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Mili=
tary theorist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_von_Clausewitz"=
 title=3D"Carl von Clausewitz">Carl von Clausewitz</a> said, "Every age has=
 its own kind of war, its own limiting conditions, and its own peculiar pre=
conceptions."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-121" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-121"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>120<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Psychoanalytic">Psychoanaly=
tic</h3></div>
<p>Dutch <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychoanalyst" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Psychoanalyst">psychoanalyst</a> <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joost_Meerloo" title=3D"Joost Meerloo">Joost Meerloo</a=
> held that, "War is often...a mass discharge of accumulated internal rage =
(where)...the inner fears of mankind are discharged in mass destruction."<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-meerloo_122-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-meerloo-122"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>121<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other psychoanal=
ysts such as E.F.M. Durban and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joh=
n_Bowlby" title=3D"John Bowlby">John Bowlby</a> have argued human beings ar=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inheritance" title=3D"Inheritanc=
e">inherently</a> violent.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-123" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-123"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>122<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This a=
ggressiveness is fueled by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Displac=
ement_(psychology)" title=3D"Displacement (psychology)">displacement</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychological_projection" title=
=3D"Psychological projection">projection</a> where a person transfers his o=
r her grievances into bias and hatred against other <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Race_(human_classification)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Race (human classification)">races</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Religion" title=3D"Religion">religions</a>, <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nation" title=3D"Nation">nations</a> or <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideology" title=3D"Ideology">ideologies</a>. By t=
his theory, the nation state preserves order in the local society while cre=
ating an outlet for aggression through warfare.
</p><p>The Italian psychoanalyst <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ranco_Fornari" title=3D"Franco Fornari">Franco Fornari</a>, a follower of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melanie_Klein" title=3D"Melanie Kle=
in">Melanie Klein</a>, thought war was the paranoid or projective "elaborat=
ion" of mourning.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-124" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-124"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>123<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Fornari thought=
 war and violence develop out of our "love need": our wish to preserve and =
defend the sacred object to which we are attached, namely our early mother =
and our fusion with her. For the adult, nations are the sacred objects that=
 generate warfare. Fornari focused upon sacrifice as the essence of war: th=
e astonishing willingness of human beings to die for their country, to give=
 over their bodies to their nation.
</p><p>Despite Fornari's theory that man's altruistic desire for self-sacri=
fice for a noble cause is a contributing factor towards war, few wars have =
originated from a desire for war among the general populace.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-125" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#=
cite_note-125"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>124<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Far more often the general population has been =
reluctantly drawn into war by its rulers. One psychological theory that loo=
ks at the leaders is advanced by Maurice Walsh.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-126" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-126=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>125<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> He argues the general populace is more neutral towards war a=
nd wars occur when leaders with a psychologically abnormal disregard for hu=
man life are placed into power. War is caused by leaders who seek war such =
as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Napoleon_I_of_France" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Napoleon I of France">Napoleon</a> and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adolf_Hitler" title=3D"Adolf Hitler">Hitler</a>.=
 Such leaders most often come to power in times of crisis when the populace=
 opts for a decisive leader, who then leads the nation to war.
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>Naturally, the common pe=
ople don't want war; neither in Russia nor in England nor in America, nor f=
or that matter in Germany. That is understood. But, after all, it is the le=
aders of the country who determine the policy and it is always a simple mat=
ter to drag the people along, whether it is a democracy or a fascist dictat=
orship or a Parliament or a Communist dictatorship. ... the people can alwa=
ys be brought to the bidding of the leaders. That is easy. All you have to =
do is tell them they are being attacked and denounce the pacifists for lack=
 of patriotism and exposing the country to danger. It works the same way in=
 any country.</p></blockquote><div class=3D"templatequotecite"><p style=3D"=
display: inline; padding-left: 2.3em;">=E2=80=94=E2=80=8A<a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_G%C3%B6ring" title=3D"Hermann G=C3=B6ring">H=
ermann G=C3=B6ring</a> at the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nure=
mberg_trials" title=3D"Nuremberg trials">Nuremberg trials</a>, 18 April 194=
6<sup id=3D"cite_ref-127" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-127"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>126<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><span style=3D"display:none" dat=
a-plural=3D"0"></span></p></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Evolutionary">Evolutionary<=
/h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prehistoric_warfare" tit=
le=3D"Prehistoric warfare">Prehistoric warfare</a></div>
<p>Several theories concern the evolutionary origins of warfare. There are =
two main schools: One sees organized warfare as emerging in or after the Me=
solithic as a result of complex social organization and greater population =
density and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Competition" title=3D"=
Competition">competition</a> over resources; the other sees human warfare a=
s a more ancient practice derived from common animal tendencies, such as te=
rritoriality and sexual competition.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-128" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-128"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>127<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>The latter school argues that since warlike behavior patterns are fo=
und in many primate species such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Common_chimpanzee" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Common chimpanzee">chim=
panzees</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ApesWar_129-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-ApesWar-129"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>128<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> a=
s well as in many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ant" title=3D"An=
t">ant</a> species,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-AntsLandmines_130-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-AntsLandmines-1=
30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>129<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> group conflict may be a general feature of animal social b=
ehavior. Some proponents of the idea argue that war, while innate, has been=
 intensified greatly by developments of technology and social organization =
such as weaponry and states.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-131" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-131"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>130<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Psychologist and linguist <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
teven_Pinker" title=3D"Steven Pinker">Steven Pinker</a> argued that war-rel=
ated behaviors may have been naturally selected in the ancestral environmen=
t due to the benefits of victory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-fn1_133-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-fn1-133"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> He also argued that in order to have credible <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deterrence_theory" title=3D"Deterrence theory">deterre=
nce</a> against other groups (as well as on an individual level), it was im=
portant to have a reputation for retaliation, causing humans to develop ins=
tincts for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Revenge" title=3D"Reven=
ge">revenge</a> as well as for protecting a group's (or an individual's) re=
putation ("<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honor" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Honor">honor</a>").<sup id=3D"cite_ref-fn1_133-1" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-fn1-133"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Reproduction_of_Bonampak_mural=
s_(panorama).JPG" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.=
wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/Reproduction_of_Bonampak_murals_=
%28panorama%29.JPG/330px-Reproduction_of_Bonampak_murals_%28panorama%29.JPG=
" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"145" class=3D"mw-file-element"=
 data-file-width=3D"8763" data-file-height=3D"4240"></a><figcaption>Increas=
ing population and constant warfare among the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Maya_warfare" title=3D"Maya warfare">Maya</a> city-states over =
resources may have contributed to the eventual <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Classic_Maya_collapse" title=3D"Classic Maya collapse">collaps=
e</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maya_civilization" ti=
tle=3D"Maya civilization">Maya civilization</a> by 900 CE.</figcaption></fi=
gure>
<p>Crofoot and Wrangham have argued that warfare, if defined as group inter=
actions in which "coalitions attempt to aggressively dominate or kill membe=
rs of other groups", is a characteristic of most human societies. Those in =
which it has been lacking "tend to be societies that were politically domin=
ated by their neighbors".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-HumanPrimateAggression_134-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-=
HumanPrimateAggression-134"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>132<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashley_Montagu" title=3D"As=
hley Montagu">Ashley Montagu</a> strongly denied universalistic instinctual=
 arguments, arguing that social factors and childhood socialization are imp=
ortant in determining the nature and presence of warfare. Thus, he argues, =
warfare is not a universal human occurrence and appears to have been a hist=
orical invention, associated with certain types of human societies.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-135" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/War#cite_note-135"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>133<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Montagu's argument is supported by eth=
nographic research conducted in societies where the concept of aggression s=
eems to be entirely absent, e.g. the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Chewong" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chewong">Chewong</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semai_people" title=3D"Semai people">Sema=
i</a> of the Malay peninsula.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-136" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-136"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>134<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Bob=
bi S. Low has observed correlation between warfare and education, noting so=
cieties where warfare is commonplace encourage their children to be more ag=
gressive.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-137" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-137"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>135<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Economic_2">Economic</h3></=
div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Disabled_Iraqi_T-54A,_T-55,_Type_59_or_Type_6=
9_tank_and_burning_Kuwaiti_oil_field.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><im=
g src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Disabled=
_Iraqi_T-54A%2C_T-55%2C_Type_59_or_Type_69_tank_and_burning_Kuwaiti_oil_fie=
ld.jpg/250px-Disabled_Iraqi_T-54A%2C_T-55%2C_Type_59_or_Type_69_tank_and_bu=
rning_Kuwaiti_oil_field.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"165=
" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2860" data-file-height=3D"18=
90"></a><figcaption>Kuwaiti <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oil_we=
ll" title=3D"Oil well">oil wells</a> on fire during the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gulf_War" title=3D"Gulf War">Gulf War</a>, 1 March 19=
91</figcaption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Resource_war" title=3D"R=
esource war">Resource war</a></div>
<p>War can be seen as a growth of economic competition in a competitive int=
ernational system. In this view wars begin as a pursuit of markets for <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_resource" title=3D"Natural res=
ource">natural resources</a> and for wealth. War has also been linked to <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_development" title=3D"Econo=
mic development">economic development</a> by economic historians and develo=
pment economists studying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/State-bu=
ilding" title=3D"State-building">state-building</a> and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiscal_capacity" title=3D"Fiscal capacity">fiscal cap=
acity</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-138" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-138"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>136<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> While this theory has =
been applied to many conflicts, such counter arguments become less valid as=
 the increasing mobility of capital and information level the distributions=
 of wealth worldwide, or when considering that it is relative, not absolute=
, wealth differences that may fuel wars. There are those on the extreme <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_(politics)" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Right (politics)">right</a> of the political spectrum who provi=
de support, fascists in particular, by asserting a natural right of a stron=
g nation to whatever the weak cannot hold by force.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-139"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note=
-139"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>137<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-140" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-140"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>138<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Marxist">Marxist</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marxist_explanations=
_of_warfare" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Marxist explanations of warfare=
">Marxist explanations of warfare</a></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marxism" title=3D"Marxism">=
Marxist</a> theory of war is quasi-economic in that it states all modern wa=
rs are caused by competition for resources and markets between great (<a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperialism" title=3D"Imperialism">impe=
rialist</a>) powers, claiming these wars are a natural result of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capitalism" title=3D"Capitalism">capitalism<=
/a>. Marxist economists <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Kauts=
ky" title=3D"Karl Kautsky">Karl Kautsky</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Rosa_Luxemburg" title=3D"Rosa Luxemburg">Rosa Luxemburg</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudolf_Hilferding" title=3D"Rudolf Hi=
lferding">Rudolf Hilferding</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Vladimir_Lenin" title=3D"Vladimir Lenin">Vladimir Lenin</a> theorized tha=
t <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperialism" title=3D"Imperialis=
m">imperialism</a> was the result of capitalist countries needing new <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Market_(economics)" title=3D"Market (ec=
onomics)">markets</a>. Expansion of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Means_of_production" title=3D"Means of production">means of productio=
n</a> is only possible if there is a corresponding growth in <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consumer_demand" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Consumer demand">consumer demand</a>. Since the workers in a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capitalist_economy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Capitalist economy">capitalist economy</a> would be unable to fill the =
demand, producers must expand into non-capitalist markets to find consumers=
 for their goods, hence driving imperialism.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-141" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-141">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>139<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Demographic">Demographic</h=
3></div>
<p>Demographic theories can be grouped into two classes, Malthusian and you=
th bulge theories:
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Malthusian">Malthusian</h4>=
</div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malthusian_catastrophe" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Malthusian catastrophe">Malthusian theories</a> s=
ee expanding population and scarce resources as a source of violent conflic=
t. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pope_Urban_II" title=3D"Pope Ur=
ban II">Pope Urban II</a> in 1095, on the eve of the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Crusade" title=3D"First Crusade">First Crusade</a>=
, advocating Crusade as a solution to European overpopulation, said:
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>For this land which you =
now inhabit, shut in on all sides by the sea and the mountain peaks, is too=
 narrow for your large population; it scarcely furnishes food enough for it=
s cultivators. Hence it is that you murder and devour one another, that you=
 wage wars, and that many among you perish in civil strife. Let hatred, the=
refore, depart from among you; let your quarrels end. Enter upon the road t=
o the Holy Sepulchre; wrest that land from a wicked race, and subject it to=
 yourselves.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-142" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-142"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>140<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>This is one of the earliest expressions of what has come to be called th=
e Malthusian theory of war, in which wars are caused by expanding populatio=
ns and limited resources. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_M=
althus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Thomas Malthus">Thomas Malthus</a> (=
1766=E2=80=931834) wrote that populations always increase until they are li=
mited by war, disease, or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Famine" =
title=3D"Famine">famine</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-143" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-143"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>141<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The =
violent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herder%E2%80%93farmer_conf=
licts_in_Nigeria" title=3D"Herder=E2=80=93farmer conflicts in Nigeria">herd=
er=E2=80=93farmer conflicts in Nigeria</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mali" title=3D"Mali">Mali</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Sudanese_nomadic_conflicts" title=3D"Sudanese nomadic conflicts">Sud=
an</a> and other countries in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Sahel" title=3D"Sahel">Sahel</a> region have been exacerbated by <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_degradation" title=3D"Land degradation"=
>land degradation</a> and population growth.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-144" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-144">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>142<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-145" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-145"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>143<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_n=
ote-146"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>144<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Youth_bulge">Youth bulge</h=
4></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:2017_world_map,_median_age_by_country.svg" cl=
ass=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipe=
dia/commons/thumb/b/b7/2017_world_map%2C_median_age_by_country.svg/500px-20=
17_world_map%2C_median_age_by_country.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"=
350" height=3D"179" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"864" data-=
file-height=3D"443"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Population_pyramid" title=3D"Population pyramid">Median age</a> by countr=
y. War reduces life expectancy. A youth bulge is evident for <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demographics_of_Africa" title=3D"Demographics of=
 Africa">Africa</a>, and to a lesser extent in some countries in West Asia,=
 South Asia, Southeast Asia and Central America.</figcaption></figure>
<p>According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunnar_Heinsohn" t=
itle=3D"Gunnar Heinsohn">Heinsohn</a>, who proposed <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Youth_bulge" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Youth bulge">=
youth bulge</a> theory in its most generalized form, a youth bulge occurs w=
hen 30 to 40 percent of the males of a nation belong to the "fighting age" =
cohorts from 15 to 29 years of age. It will follow periods with <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Total_fertility_rate" title=3D"Total fertilit=
y rate">total fertility rates</a> as high as 4=E2=80=938 children per woman=
 with a 15=E2=80=9329-year delay.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-147" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-147"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>145<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-148" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-148"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>146<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Heinsohn saw both past "Christi=
anist" European colonialism and imperialism, as well as today's Islamist ci=
vil unrest and terrorism as results of high birth rates producing youth bul=
ges.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-149" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-149"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>147<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>Among prominent historical events that have been attributed to youth=
 bulges are the role played by the historically large youth cohorts in the =
rebellion and revolution waves of early modern Europe, including the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Revolution" title=3D"French Revol=
ution">French Revolution</a> of 1789,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-150" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-150"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>148<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> and the effect of economic depression upon the largest German youth co=
horts ever in explaining the rise of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Nazism" title=3D"Nazism">Nazism</a> in Germany in the 1930s.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-151" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
ar#cite_note-151"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>149<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The 1994 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Rwandan_genocide" title=3D"Rwandan genocide">Rwandan genocide</a> has=
 also been analyzed as following a massive youth bulge.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
152" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_=
note-152"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>150<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> Youth bulge theory has been subjected to statistical=
 analysis by the World Bank,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-153" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-153"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>151<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Population_Action_International" title=
=3D"Population Action International">Population Action International</a>,<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-154" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/War#cite_note-154"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>152<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Berlin_Institute_for_Population_and_Development" title=3D"Be=
rlin Institute for Population and Development">Berlin Institute for Populat=
ion and Development</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-155" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-155"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>153<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Youth bu=
lge theories have been criticized as leading to racial, gender and age disc=
rimination.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-156" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-156"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>154<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cultural">Cultural</h3></di=
v>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geoffrey_Parker_(historian)" ti=
tle=3D"Geoffrey Parker (historian)">Geoffrey Parker</a> argues that what di=
stinguishes the "Western way of war" based in Western Europe chiefly allows=
 historians to explain its extraordinary success in conquering most of the =
world after 1500:</p><blockquote><p> The Western way of war rests upon five=
 principal foundations: technology, discipline, a highly aggressive militar=
y tradition, a remarkable capacity to innovate and to respond rapidly to th=
e innovation of others and&nbsp;=E2=80=93 from about 1500 onward&nbsp;=E2=
=80=93 a unique system of war finance. The combination of all five provided=
 a formula for military success....The outcome of wars has been determined =
less by technology, then by better war plans, the achievement of surprise, =
greater economic strength, and above all superior discipline.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-157" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War=
#cite_note-157"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>155<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Parker argues that Western armies were stronger because they emphasized =
discipline, that is, "the ability of a formation to stand fast in the face =
of the enemy, where they're attacking or being attacked, without giving way=
 to the natural impulse of fear and panic." Discipline came from drills and=
 marching in formation, target practice, and creating small "artificial kin=
ship groups: such as the company and the platoon, to enhance psychological =
cohesion and combat efficiency.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-158" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-158"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>156<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rationalist">Rationalist</h=
3></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rationalism_(international_rela=
tions)" title=3D"Rationalism (international relations)">Rationalism</a> is =
an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_relations_theory"=
 title=3D"International relations theory">international relations theory</a=
> or framework. Rationalism (and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
eorealism_(international_relations)" title=3D"Neorealism (international rel=
ations)">Neorealism (international relations)</a>) operate under the assump=
tion that states or international actors are rational, seek the best possib=
le outcomes for themselves, and desire to avoid the costs of war.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-:0_159-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/War#cite_note-:0-159"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>157<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Under one <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Game_theory" title=3D"Game theory">game theory</a> approac=
h, rationalist theories posit all actors can <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Bargaining_model_of_war" title=3D"Bargaining model of war">barga=
in</a>, would be better off if war did not occur, and likewise seek to unde=
rstand why war nonetheless reoccurs. Under another rationalist game theory =
without bargaining, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peace_war_=
game" title=3D"Peace war game">peace war game</a>, optimal strategies can s=
till be found that depend upon number of iterations played. In "Rationalist=
 Explanations for War", <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Fear=
on" title=3D"James Fearon">James Fearon</a> examined three rationalist expl=
anations for why some countries engage in war:
</p>
<ul><li>Issue indivisibilities</li>
<li>Incentives to misrepresent or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Information_asymmetry" title=3D"Information asymmetry">information asymmetr=
y</a></li>
<li>Commitment problems<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_159-1" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-:0-159"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>157<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></=
li></ul>
<p>"Issue indivisibility" occurs when the two parties cannot avoid war by b=
argaining, because the thing over which they are fighting cannot be shared =
between them, but only owned entirely by one side or the other. "<a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_asymmetry" title=3D"Information =
asymmetry">Information asymmetry</a> with incentives to misrepresent" occur=
s when two countries have secrets about their individual capabilities, and =
do not agree on either: who would win a war between them, or the magnitude =
of state's victory or loss. For instance, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Geoffrey_Blainey" title=3D"Geoffrey Blainey">Geoffrey Blainey</a> a=
rgues that war is a result of miscalculation of strength. He cites historic=
al examples of war and demonstrates, "war is usually the outcome of a diplo=
matic crisis which cannot be solved because both sides have conflicting est=
imates of their bargaining power."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-160" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-160"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>158<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Thirdly, bargaining may fail due to the states' inability to make credibl=
e commitments.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-161" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-161"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>159<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Within the rationalist tradition, some theorists have suggested that=
 individuals engaged in war suffer a normal level of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognitive_bias" title=3D"Cognitive bias">cognitive bias<=
/a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-162" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-162"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>160<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but are still "as rational a=
s you and me".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-163" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-163"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>161<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> According to philo=
sopher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iain_King" title=3D"Iain Ki=
ng">Iain King</a>, "Most instigators of conflict overrate their chances of =
success, while most participants underrate their chances of injury...."<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-164" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/War#cite_note-164"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>162<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> King asserts that "Most catastrophic=
 military decisions are rooted in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Groupthink" title=3D"Groupthink">groupthink</a>" which is faulty, but still=
 rational.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-165" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-165"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>163<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The rationalist theory=
 focused around bargaining, which is currently under debate. The Iraq War p=
roved to be an anomaly that undercuts the validity of applying rationalist =
theory to some wars.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-166" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-166"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>164<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Political_science">Politica=
l science</h3></div>
<p>The statistical analysis of war was pioneered by <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Lewis_Fry_Richardson" title=3D"Lewis Fry Richardson">Lewi=
s Fry Richardson</a> following <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wor=
ld_War_I" title=3D"World War I">World War I</a>. More recent databases of w=
ars and armed conflict have been assembled by the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Correlates_of_War" title=3D"Correlates of War">Correlates o=
f War</a> Project, Peter Brecke and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Uppsala_Conflict_Data_Program" title=3D"Uppsala Conflict Data Program=
">Uppsala Conflict Data Program</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-UCDP_167-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-UCDP-=
167"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>165<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> The following subsections consider causes of war from sys=
tem, societal, and individual levels of analysis. This kind of division was=
 first proposed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenneth_Waltz" =
title=3D"Kenneth Waltz">Kenneth Waltz</a> in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Man,_the_State,_and_War" title=3D"Man, the State, and War">Ma=
n, the State, and War</a></i> and has been often used by political scientis=
ts since then.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Levy1998_168-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 143">:=E2=
=80=8A143=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"System-level">System-level<=
/h4></div>
<p>There are several different <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Int=
ernational_relations_theory" title=3D"International relations theory">inter=
national relations theory</a> schools. Supporters of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Realism_in_international_relations" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Realism in international relations">realism in international rel=
ations</a> argue that the motivation of states is the quest for security, a=
nd conflicts can arise from the inability to distinguish defense from offen=
se, which is called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Security_d=
ilemma" title=3D"Security dilemma">security dilemma</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Levy1998_168-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap">=
<span title=3D"Page / location: 145">:=E2=80=8A145=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>Within the realist school as represented by scholars such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Kissinger" title=3D"Henry Kissinger=
">Henry Kissinger</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hans_Mor=
genthau" title=3D"Hans Morgenthau">Hans Morgenthau</a>, and the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neorealism_(international_relations)" title=
=3D"Neorealism (international relations)">neorealist</a> school represented=
 by scholars such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenneth_Waltz=
" title=3D"Kenneth Waltz">Kenneth Waltz</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/John_Mearsheimer" title=3D"John Mearsheimer">John Mearsheimer=
</a>, two main sub-theories are:
</p>
<ol><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Balance_of_power_(internat=
ional_relations)" title=3D"Balance of power (international relations)">Bala=
nce of power</a> theory: States have the goal of preventing a single state =
from becoming a hegemon, and war is the result of the would-be hegemon's pe=
rsistent attempts at power acquisition. In this view, an international syst=
em with more equal distribution of power is more stable, and "movements tow=
ard unipolarity are destabilizing."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Levy1998_168-2" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Levy=
1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page /=
 location: 147">:=E2=80=8A147=E2=80=8A</span></sup> However, evidence has s=
hown power <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polarity_(international=
_relations)" title=3D"Polarity (international relations)">polarity</a> is n=
ot actually a major factor in the occurrence of wars.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Le=
vy1998_168-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><sp=
an title=3D"Page / location: 147=E2=80=9348">:=E2=80=8A147=E2=80=9348=E2=80=
=8A</span></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_transition_theory" title=
=3D"Power transition theory">Power transition theory</a>: Hegemons impose s=
tabilizing conditions on the world order, but they eventually decline, and =
war occurs when a declining hegemon is challenged by another rising power o=
r aims to pre-emptively suppress them. On this view, unlike for balance-of-=
power theory, wars become <i>more</i> probable when power is more equally d=
istributed. This "power preponderance" hypothesis has empirical support.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-Levy1998_168-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>166<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"re=
ference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 148">:=E2=80=8A148=E2=80=8A=
</span></sup></li></ol>
<p>The two theories are not mutually exclusive and may be used to explain d=
isparate events according to the circumstance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Levy1998_=
168-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cit=
e_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span titl=
e=3D"Page / location: 148">:=E2=80=8A148=E2=80=8A</span></sup> <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liberalism_(international_relations)" title=3D=
"Liberalism (international relations)">Liberalism</a> as it relates to inte=
rnational relations emphasizes factors such as trade, and its role in disin=
centivizing conflict which will damage economic relations. Critics respond =
that military force may sometimes be at least as effective as trade at achi=
eving economic benefits, especially historically if not as much today.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-Levy1998_168-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>166<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"refe=
rence nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 149">:=E2=80=8A149=E2=80=8A</=
span></sup> Furthermore, trade relations which result in a high level of de=
pendency may escalate tensions and lead to conflict. Empirical data on the =
relationship of trade to peace are mixed, and moreover, some evidence sugge=
sts countries at war do not necessarily trade less with each other.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Levy1998_168-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>166<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"refere=
nce nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 150">:=E2=80=8A150=E2=80=8A</sp=
an></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Societal-level">Societal-le=
vel</h4></div>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diversionary_foreign_polic=
y" title=3D"Diversionary foreign policy">Diversionary theory</a>, also know=
n as the "scapegoat hypothesis", suggests the politically powerful may use =
war to as a diversion or to rally domestic popular support.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Levy1998_168-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowra=
p"><span title=3D"Page / location: 152">:=E2=80=8A152=E2=80=8A</span></sup>=
 This is supported by literature showing out-group hostility <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Realistic_conflict_theory" title=3D"Realistic co=
nflict theory">enhances</a> in-group <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Group_cohesiveness" title=3D"Group cohesiveness">bonding</a>, and a sign=
ificant domestic "rally effect" has been demonstrated when conflicts begin.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Levy1998_168-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>166<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D=
"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 152=E2=80=9313">:=E2=80=
=8A152=E2=80=9313=E2=80=8A</span></sup> However, studies examining the incr=
eased use of force as a function of need for internal political support are=
 more mixed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Levy1998_168-10" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 152=E2=80=
=9353">:=E2=80=8A152=E2=80=9353=E2=80=8A</span></sup> U.S. war-time preside=
ntial popularity surveys taken during the presidencies of several recent U.=
S. leaders have supported diversionary theory.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-MilitaryA=
dventurism_169-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/War#cite_note-MilitaryAdventurism-169"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>167<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Individual-level">Individua=
l-level</h4></div>
<p>These theories suggest differences in people's personalities, decision-m=
aking, emotions, belief systems, and biases are important in determining wh=
ether conflicts get out of hand. For instance, it has been proposed that co=
nflict is modulated by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bounded_rat=
ionality" title=3D"Bounded rationality">bounded rationality</a> and various=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cognitive_biases" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Cognitive biases">cognitive biases</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
Levy1998_168-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/War#cite_note-Levy1998-168"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>166<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap">=
<span title=3D"Page / location: 157">:=E2=80=8A157=E2=80=8A</span></sup> su=
ch as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prospect_theory" title=3D"Pr=
ospect theory">prospect theory</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Levy1997_170-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Levy=
1997-170"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>168<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Ethics">Ethics</h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:1871_Vereshchagin_Apotheose_de=
s_Krieges_anagoria.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://u=
pload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f0/1871_Vereshchagin_Apotheos=
e_des_Krieges_anagoria.JPG/250px-1871_Vereshchagin_Apotheose_des_Krieges_an=
agoria.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"163" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-element" data-file-width=3D"3172" data-file-height=3D"2064"></a><figcapti=
on><i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Apotheosis_of_War" title=
=3D"The Apotheosis of War">The Apotheosis of War</a></i> (1871) by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vasily_Vereshchagin" title=3D"Vasily Vere=
shchagin">Vasily Vereshchagin</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morality" title=3D"Morality=
">morality</a> of war has been the subject of debate for thousands of years=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DeForrest_171-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-DeForrest-171"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>169<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The two principal aspects of ethics in war, according to the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Just_war_theory" title=3D"Just war theory=
">just war theory</a>, are <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jus_=
ad_bellum" title=3D"Jus ad bellum">jus ad bellum</a></i> and <i><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jus_in_bello" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Jus in bello">jus in bello</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-172" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-172"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>170<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p><p><i>Jus ad bellum</i> (right to war), dictates which unfriendly acts =
and circumstances justify a proper authority in declaring war on another na=
tion. There are six main criteria for the declaration of a just war: first,=
 any just war must be declared by a lawful authority; second, it must be a =
just and righteous cause, with sufficient gravity to merit large-scale viol=
ence; third, the just belligerent must have rightful intentions =E2=80=93 n=
amely, that they seek to advance good and curtail evil; fourth, a just bell=
igerent must have a reasonable chance of success; fifth, the war must be a =
last resort; and sixth, the ends being sought must be proportional to means=
 being used.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-173" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-173"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>171<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
74" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_n=
ote-174"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>172<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:RIAN_archive_324_In_besieged_Leningrad.jpg" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikip=
edia/commons/thumb/e/e5/RIAN_archive_324_In_besieged_Leningrad.jpg/250px-RI=
AN_archive_324_In_besieged_Leningrad.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" =
height=3D"178" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"4096" data-file=
-height=3D"2912"></a><figcaption>In besieged <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Leningrad" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Leningrad">Leningrad</=
a>. "Hitler ordered that Moscow and Leningrad were to be razed to the groun=
d; their inhabitants were to be annihilated or driven out by starvation. Th=
ese intentions were part of the '<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G=
eneral_Plan_East" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"General Plan East">General=
 Plan East</a>'." =E2=80=93 <i>The Oxford Companion to World War II.</i><su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-175" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/War#cite_note-175"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>173<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure><p><i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jus_in_bello" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Jus in bello">Jus in bello</a></i> (right in war), is the set of ethica=
l rules when conducting war. The two main principles are proportionality an=
d discrimination. Proportionality regards how much force is necessary and m=
orally appropriate to the ends being sought and the injustice suffered. The=
 principle of discrimination determines who are the legitimate targets in a=
 war, and specifically makes a separation between combatants, who it is per=
missible to kill, and non-combatants, who it is not.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mos=
eley_176-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wa=
r#cite_note-Moseley-176"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>174<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Failure to follow these rules can res=
ult in the loss of legitimacy for the just-war-belligerent.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Codevilla,_Seabury_1989_304_177-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-Codevilla,_Seabury_1989_304-177"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>175<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>The just war theory was foundational in the creation of the United N=
ations and in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_law" t=
itle=3D"International law">international law</a>'s regulations on legitimat=
e war.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DeForrest_171-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-DeForrest-171"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>169<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Lewis Coser, an American conflict theorist and sociologist, argued t=
hat conflict provides a function and a process whereby a succession of new =
equilibriums are created. Thus, the struggle of opposing forces, rather tha=
n being disruptive, may be a means of balancing and maintaining a social st=
ructure or society.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-178" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-178"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>176<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Limiting_and_stopping">Limi=
ting and stopping</h2></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Washington_March15_2003-02.jpg" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons=
/thumb/9/9f/Washington_March15_2003-02.jpg/250px-Washington_March15_2003-02=
.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-elem=
ent" data-file-width=3D"1600" data-file-height=3D"1200"></a><figcaption>Ant=
i-war rally in Washington, D.C., 15 March 2003</figcaption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-war_movement" t=
itle=3D"Anti-war movement">Anti-war movement</a></div><p>Religious groups h=
ave long formally opposed or sought to limit war as in the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Vatican_Council" title=3D"Second Vatican Co=
uncil">Second Vatican Council</a> document <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Gaudium_et_spes" title=3D"Gaudium et spes">Gaudiem et Spes</a><=
/i>: "Any act of war aimed indiscriminately at the destruction of entire ci=
ties of extensive areas along with their population is a crime against God =
and man himself. It merits unequivocal and unhesitating condemnation."<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-179" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/War#cite_note-179"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>177<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Anti-war movements have existed for every major war in the 20th cent=
ury, including, most prominently, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
World_War_I" title=3D"World War I">World War I</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/World_War_II" title=3D"World War II">World War II</a>, an=
d the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vietnam_War" title=3D"Vietna=
m War">Vietnam War</a>. In the 21st century, worldwide anti-war movements o=
ccurred in response to the United States <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%932021)" title=3D"War in Afghanistan =
(2001=E2=80=932021)">invasion of Afghanistan</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Iraq_War" title=3D"Iraq War">Iraq</a>. Protests <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opposition_to_the_War_in_Afghanistan_(200=
1%E2%80%932021)" title=3D"Opposition to the War in Afghanistan (2001=E2=80=
=932021)">opposing the War in Afghanistan</a> occurred in Europe, Asia, and=
 the United States.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Pauses">Pauses</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ceasefire" title=3D=
"Ceasefire">Ceasefire</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armi=
stice" title=3D"Armistice">Armistice</a></div>
<p>During a war, the parties may agree to pauses. A ceasefire is a stoppage=
 of a war in which each side agrees with the other to suspend aggressive ac=
tions (often due to mediation by a third party).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:32_180=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_n=
ote-:32-180"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>178<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> Ceasefires may be declared as part of a formal <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty" title=3D"Treaty">treaty</a> =
but also as part of an informal understanding between opposing forces.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-:02_181-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-:02-181"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>179=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A ceasefire can be temporar=
y with an intended end date or may be intended to last indefinitely. A ceas=
efire is distinct from an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Armistic=
e" title=3D"Armistice">armistice</a> in that the armistice is a formal end =
to a war whereas a ceasefire may be a temporary stoppage.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-182" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cit=
e_note-182"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>180<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The immediate goal of a ceasefire is to stop violence but the underl=
ying purposes of ceasefires vary. Ceasefires may be intended to meet short-=
term limited needs (such as providing humanitarian aid), manage a conflict =
to make it less devastating, or advance efforts to peacefully resolve a dis=
pute.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:22_183-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-:22-183"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>181<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An actor may not =
always intend for a ceasefire to advance the peaceful resolution of a confl=
ict but instead give the actor an upper hand in the conflict (for example, =
by re-arming and repositioning forces or attacking an unsuspecting adversar=
y), which creates <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bargaining_model=
_of_war" title=3D"Bargaining model of war">bargaining problems</a> that may=
 make ceasefires less likely to be implemented and less likely to be durabl=
e if implemented.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:33_184-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-:33-184"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>182<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-:22_183-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/War#cite_note-:22-183"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>181<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-185" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#cite_note-185"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>183<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>The durability of ceasefire agreements is affected by several factor=
s, such as demilitarized zones, withdrawal of troops and third-party guaran=
tees and monitoring (e.g. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peacekee=
ping" title=3D"Peacekeeping">peacekeeping</a>). Ceasefire agreements are mo=
re likely to be durable when they reduce incentives to attack, reduce uncer=
tainty about the adversary's intentions, and when mechanisms are put in pla=
ce to prevent accidents from spiraling into conflict.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:3=
3_184-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War#c=
ite_note-:33-184"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>182<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
